  }, "You\u2019ll achieve more if you set clear and reachable goals")), mdx("h4", {
    "id": "first-necessity-of-a-goal-in-order-to-move-anywhere"
  }, "First, necessity of a goal in order to move anywhere."), mdx("p", null, "Human psyche is less like a GPS-navigator and more like a pretty advanced cruise-control. It maintains speed and direction, it keeps you in the lane, it tries to keep\ndistance from things in your way, it will even hit an emergency break if you are about to hit a wall or jump off a cliff (problem is momentum \u2014 break as hard as you\nwant, sometimes you notice a cliff way too late). It does not care about some abstract goal \u2014 remaining on the current path is a goal in itself. Vast majority of\npeople live without any goals whatsoever \u2014 they \u201Cdrift along\u201D, \u201Cflow with the current\u201D, etc.. Even when they achieve something \u2014 it\u2019s not because of some innate\ndrive, but merely because they think it\u2019s a natural progression of events (yeah, they are living out a story they\u2019ve heard somewhere). Work, kill time at home, sleep,\nrepeat. I myself achieved quite a lot in life just by living from crisis to crisis with longest term goal being \u201Cnot starving in the next month\u201D. Life throws those\n\u201Coh, shit\u201D moments at you, you resolve them and become stronger without ever planning for it. And between those are long streaks of boredom because if Universe will\nnot force you to do something, you yourself surely won\u2019t. If human\u2019s innate nature required having a goal, why would we need self-help gurus to remind us about\nsetting goals?"), mdx("h4", {
    "id": "second-claim-that-you-need-a-clear-goal-to-achieve-anything-in-life"
  }, "Second, claim that you need a clear goal to achieve anything in life."), mdx("p", null, "It\u2019s basically the opposite: the more vague your goal is \u2014 the better. Let\u2019s start with\na simple picture: on one side we have a heroin addict in withdrawal, who has a crystal clear goal of getting next dose and will ignore anything on his way\ntowards this goal, on the other side we have a buddhist monk, whose philosophy prescribes him to avoid any striving towards a specific goal\n(", mdx("a", _extends({
