    "target": "_blank",
    "rel": "noreferrer"
  }), "non-action"), "). I would argue that goal-avoiding monk is more enlightened and successful than a goal-oriented drug addict.\nThis is a cherry-picked example, clearly it cannot be a universal truth. Well, let me demonstrate how \u201Cclear\u201D goal setting can only bring you suffering.\nIt\u2019s quite easy to relate to why missing you goal is unpleasant: self-doubt, feeling helpless and inadequate \u2014 lizard-brain (or is it lobster-brain these days)\ntells you that if you keep going like this you\u2019ll end up dead soon. It\u2019s less easy to understand why achieving goal is bad. It\u2019s all about emotional investment.\nIn order to really hit the mark you often need to put all you have on the line, identify with the goal, but achieving the goal destroys it and big part of your\nego with that. Remember stories about people who worked hard to become rich end up more miserable than before? Stories about carrying out a perfect revenge\nbringing emptiness instead of joy? Stories about trying really hard to \u201Cwin that girl\u201D only to achieve it and realize that this goal was dumb all along? Andrew Wiggin\nsaid it best:"), mdx("blockquote", null, mdx("p", {
